{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011CcsRjCLk75vwr84foXuaM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All goals verified:\n\n- **app-producer**: `1/1 Running`, `0` restarts, deployment `1/1` Ready/Available, messages actively publishing (queue grew 11→17 in 5s).\n- **`/app` vhost**: contains `app-queue`, type `classic`, with messages.\n- **RabbitMQ cluster**: StatefulSet `3/3` ready, all 3 nodes (`rabbitmq-0/1/2`) running and clustered, no partitions.\n\n**Root causes found and fixed:**\n1. An external process had scaled the StatefulSet down to 1 replica and deleted `rabbitmq-1`/`rabbitmq-2` pods (backed by ephemeral `emptyDir` volumes, so their data was wiped), then scaled back to 3 — but the default `OrderedReady` pod management policy created a deadlock: `rabbitmq-1` couldn't become Ready without Mnesia-syncing with `rabbitmq-2`, which the StatefulSet wouldn't create until `rabbitmq-1` was Ready. I recreated the StatefulSet (orphan-delete + reapply) with `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` to break the deadlock, then manually reconciled cluster membership (`force_boot` on rabbitmq-0, `reset`/`join_cluster` on rabbitmq-2) since the fresh nodes had conflicting identities with the surviving disk node (rabbitmq-0, which kept its original data intact throughout — no data loss).\n2. Separately, `app-user`'s permissions on the `/app` vhost had an **empty `configure` permission**, causing `not_authorised` when the producer tried to declare `app-queue`. Fixed with `rabbitmqctl set_permissions -p /app app-user \".*\" \".*\" \".*\"`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1049,"cache_read_input_tokens":92498,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1049},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3fb2359b-9b20-4640-bc08-db4382155585","uuid":"89295580-ce94-45b8-bc8d-67b7a5040dea","request_id":"req_011CcsRjBAoTebzJ5nwDkYjz"}
{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":740042,"duration_api_ms":282486,"ttft_ms":1633,"ttft_stream_ms":1418,"time_to_request_ms":113,"num_turns":47,"result":"All goals verified:\n\n- **app-producer**: `1/1 Running`, `0` restarts, deployment `1/1` Ready/Available, messages actively publishing (queue grew 11→17 in 5s).\n- **`/app` vhost**: contains `app-queue`, type `classic`, with messages.\n- **RabbitMQ cluster**: StatefulSet `3/3` ready, all 3 nodes (`rabbitmq-0/1/2`) running and clustered, no partitions.\n\n**Root causes found and fixed:**\n1. An external process had scaled the StatefulSet down to 1 replica and deleted `rabbitmq-1`/`rabbitmq-2` pods (backed by ephemeral `emptyDir` volumes, so their data was wiped), then scaled back to 3 — but the default `OrderedReady` pod management policy created a deadlock: `rabbitmq-1` couldn't become Ready without Mnesia-syncing with `rabbitmq-2`, which the StatefulSet wouldn't create until `rabbitmq-1` was Ready. I recreated the StatefulSet (orphan-delete + reapply) with `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` to break the deadlock, then manually reconciled cluster membership (`force_boot` on rabbitmq-0, `reset`/`join_cluster` on rabbitmq-2) since the fresh nodes had conflicting identities with the surviving disk node (rabbitmq-0, which kept its original data intact throughout — no data loss).\n2. Separately, `app-user`'s permissions on the `/app` vhost had an **empty `configure` permission**, causing `not_authorised` when the producer tried to declare `app-queue`. Fixed with `rabbitmqctl set_permissions -p /app app-user \".*\" \".*\" \".*\"`.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"3fb2359b-9b20-4640-bc08-db4382155585","total_cost_usd":1.6591353000000002,"usage":{"input_tokens":5248,"cache_creation_input_tokens":75504,"cache_read_input_tokens":2963351,"output_tokens":20016,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation